**Derivation**

1. **Hubble distance & linear term.**  
   \[
   \frac{c}{H_0}= \frac{299\,792.458\ \text{km s}^{-1}}{70.0\ \text{km s}^{-1}\,\text{Mpc}^{-1}}
   = 4283.46\ \text{Mpc}
   \]
   \[
   \frac{cz}{H_0}= \frac{299\,792.458\ \text{km s}^{-1}\times 0.200}{70.0\ \text{km s}^{-1}\,\text{Mpc}^{-1}}
   = 856.7\ \text{Mpc}
   \]

2. **ΛCDM (q₀ = −0.55).**  
   \[
   1 + \frac{(1 - q_0)z}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{(1 - (-0.55))\times 0.2}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{1.55 \times 0.2}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{0.31}{2}
   = 1 + 0.155
   = 1.155
   \]
   \[
   d_L = \frac{cz}{H_0}\times 1.155 = 856.7 \times 1.155 \approx 990.0\ \text{Mpc}
   \]

3. **EdS (q₀ = +0.5).**  
   \[
   1 + \frac{(1 - q_0)z}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{(1 - 0.5)\times 0.2}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{0.5 \times 0.2}{2}
   = 1 + \frac{0.1}{2}
   = 1 + 0.05
   = 1.05
   \]
   \[
   d_L = \frac{cz}{H_0}\times 1.05 = 856.7 \times 1.05 \approx 900.2\ \text{Mpc}
   \]

4. **The 1998 result.**  
   A supernova at \(z = 0.2\) appearing **fainter** than the Einstein‑de Sitter prediction implies a **larger** luminosity distance, i.e., a larger factor \([1 + (1-q_0)z/2]\). This occurs when \(q_0\) is **more negative**, indicating an accelerating universe. The 1998 discovery of such fainter high‑redshift supernovae provided the first strong evidence for dark energy (accelerated expansion), favoring the ΛCDM model with \(q_0 \approx -0.55\).

**FINAL ANSWER**

\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{dl\_eds\_mpc}          &= 900.2 \\
\mathrm{dl\_lcdm\_mpc}         &= 990.0 \\
\mathrm{dl\_linear\_mpc}       &= 856.7 \\
\mathrm{hubble\_distance\_mpc} &= 4283.5 \\
\end{aligned}
\]

